  <section style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 10px; font-size:18px;">Mothballs: why they don’t work</h2>
    <p style="margin:0 0 10px;">
      Mothballs get suggested because the smell is strong, but outdoor burrows are
      a bad environment for “smell-based” control. The odor doesn’t stay trapped
      and burrow systems often have multiple openings.
    </p>
    <ul style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
      <li><strong>Outdoor airflow:</strong> tunnels vent through entrances and cracks.</li>
      <li><strong>Odor fades fast:</strong> moisture, wind, and soil contact weaken it.</li>
      <li><strong>Burrow complexity:</strong> groundhogs can use alternate exits or deeper chambers.</li>
      <li><strong>Safety concerns:</strong> mothballs aren’t a safe DIY “repellent” around pets/kids.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin:12px 0 0;">
      <strong>Bottom line:</strong> mothballs are unreliable and can create unnecessary risks.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 10px; font-size:18px;">Ammonia: temporary irritation, not a solution</h2>
    <p style="margin:0 0 10px;">
      Ammonia may irritate an animal briefly, but it’s not “sticky” in a burrow.
      Most DIY applications (rags, poured liquid, sprayed solution) lose potency
      quickly outdoors.
    </p>
    <ul style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
      <li><strong>Fumes escape:</strong> burrow openings vent ammonia rapidly.</li>
      <li><strong>Soil neutralizes:</strong> moisture and soil contact reduce the smell.</li>
      <li><strong>Groundhogs adapt:</strong> they may wait it out or dig around the area.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin:12px 0 0;">
      <strong>Bottom line:</strong> ammonia often delays proper exclusion and repair.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 10px; font-size:18px;">Ultrasonic repellents: why sound doesn’t stop groundhogs</h2>
    <p style="margin:0 0 10px;">
      Ultrasonic “stakes” claim to repel pests with sound or vibration, but soil
      absorbs and blocks these signals quickly. Burrow systems can extend well
      beyond where a device has any noticeable effect.
    </p>
    <ul style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
      <li><strong>Poor underground transmission:</strong> high-frequency sound doesn’t travel far through soil.</li>
      <li><strong>Limited coverage:</strong> a burrow network can extend beyond your yard’s visible area.</li>
      <li><strong>Behavioral workaround:</strong> animals can shift deeper or reroute tunnels.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin:12px 0 0;">
      <strong>Bottom line:</strong> ultrasonic repellents aren’t a reliable groundhog solution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 10px; font-size:18px;">Why repellents fail in general</h2>
    <p style="margin:0;">
      Groundhogs are strongly motivated by <strong>shelter</strong>, <strong>safety</strong>, and{" "}
      <strong>food access</strong>. If a burrow location provides those benefits, mild discomfort
      from smell or sound is often tolerated. Repellents also don’t remove entrances, tunnels,
      or the site conditions that made the area attractive.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 10px; font-size:18px;">What to do instead (safe order)</h2>
    <ol style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
      <li><strong>Confirm activity:</strong> smooth dirt at entrances and check for fresh digging within 24–48 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Find all entrances:</strong> walk fence lines, brush edges, and under-deck openings.</li>
      <li><strong>Don’t seal an active burrow:</strong> avoid trapping an animal inside and creating odor issues.</li>
      <li><strong>Remove or exclude:</strong> once the animal is out (or removed), prevent re-entry.</li>
      <li><strong>Install barriers:</strong> heavy-gauge hardware cloth; bury it and consider an outward “L” footer.</li>
      <li><strong>Backfill and compact:</strong> fill in lifts and compact to reduce future settling and collapse.</li>
    </ol>
    <p style="margin:12px 0 0;">
      If the burrow runs under a deck, shed, steps, patio, or slab, consider professional help
      so you don’t miss an exit or create a larger settlement problem.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 10px; font-size:18px;">Common mistakes</h2>
    <ul style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
      <li>Relying on repellents alone after a burrow is established.</li>
      <li>Sealing or filling while the burrow is active.</li>
      <li>Missing escape exits and only treating one entrance.</li>
      <li>Backfilling without compaction (future sinkholes).</li>
      <li>Repairing patios/steps/decks before stopping the burrowing (damage returns).</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

